        "created_at": "2026-01-16T17:12:58.637Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I’d like to propose a small UX improvement for message receive sounds on iOS.</p>\n<p>The problem is that currently the same notification sound plays when a message arrived when signal is in the background and when a message arrived when said sender’s chat conversation is active (on the foreground)</p>\n<p>When the user is actively reading a chat, playing the full notification tone can feel unnecessarily loud and disruptive, especially in quiet environments or when receiving multiple messages in quick succession.</p>\n<p>My proposal is: play a different more subtle sound effect when a chat is active and a message within that chat arrives (preferably the default iOS message receive notification sound or a subtle click). When signal is closed/in the background/lock screen, continue using the existing notification sound. If someone still wants the old behavior (same notification when in chat and when locked) there can be a simple switch on the notification settings like (Use legacy sound effects).</p>\n<p>This change provides audible feedback that a message arrived while avoiding disruptive volume, matches behavior seen in other iOS messaging services, keeping it consistent across the OS, does not change notification behavior or user configured notification sounds and adds minimal UI/settings impact, keeping the app simple as intended.</p>\n<p>if this direction seems reasonable, I’d be happy to explore a PR on GitHub.</p>\n<p>Thanks in advance.</p>",
